  "doi": "10.1126/science.adx3162",
  "title": "Overcoming T cell tolerance to tumor self-antigens through catch-bond engineering.",
  "journal": "Science (New York, N.Y.)",
  "year": 2026,
  "authors": "Chen X, Mao Z, Kolawole EM, Persechino M, Jude KM, Ogishi M, Mo KC, McLaughlin J, Cheng D, Xiang X, Yang X, Gee C, Liu S, Yang A, Obenaus M, Wang N, Noguchi M, Stoyanova T, Lee JK, Good Z, Latorraca NR, Evavold BD, Witte ON, Garcia KC."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study engineered a T cell receptor (TCR) targeting prostatic acid phosphatase (PAP), a nonmutated tumor-associated antigen, to overcome central tolerance that normally renders such tumor self-antigens poorly immunogenic. By identifying and mutating a \"catch-bond hotspot\" in the TCR, the authors increased the lifetime of TCR-pMHC binding under mechanical force while maintaining normal affinities and antigen specificity, thereby substantially enhancing T cell expansion, effector function, and tumor killing in vivo. Crystal structures and molecular dynamics showed that a single amino acid substitution at this hotspot facilitates peptide interaction through water reorganization at the TCR-pMHC interface. This work demonstrates that catch-bond engineering\u2014a mechanistically guided approach exploiting force-dependent binding\u2014offers a biophysical strategy to convert weakly reactive, tolerized anti-tumor T cells into potent therapeutic killers, with direct implications for TCR-T cell therapy design against self-antigens in cancer.",
